[16:52:57] ## The article's spine
[16:52:57] 
[16:52:57] The blog-specific angle here turned out to be the failure itself. A PubMed search for a 28-day turnover returns **zero papers**, and the paper everyone cites as the origin is one I could not open. So the article says exactly that, and refuses to name it as the source. It also refuses the tempting counter-move: I do *not* claim "28日は嘘" or "正しくは40日", because 39/45/47–48 don't agree with each other either — Iizuka got 47–48 by *recomputing Weinstein's own data*, which is the most interesting fact in the piece. The one action offered is free: stop judging a product at one month, since that deadline traces back to a number with no findable source.
[16:52:57] 
[16:52:57] All six references match PubMed's title/author/year/volume/pages exactly, so the downstream machine check should pass. 6,381 chars, both required sections present.
